I'm kind of wondering if the solution is to use double the stack space in exchange for more accurate, Python-like behaviour. So we have something like

```
template <typename T>
class __Pyx_Optional {
    private:
       // only one of "a" or "b" holds a value at a time
       std::optional<T> a;
       std::optional<T> b;
   public:
       template <typename ...Args>
      void emplace(Args...&& args) {
          if (a) {
             b.emplace(...args);
             a.reset();
          } else {
             a.emplace(...args);
             b.reset();
          }
      }
};
```

It's obviously a trade-off, but given that the objective was to make stack-allocated classes behave more like Python objects it might be worthwhile.

-----------------------------------

Or possibly to change the `cf_may_be_null` check to understand C++ classes a bit more. So to read

```
a = some_cppclass(2)
```

as

```
del a
a = some_cpp_class()
```
